# Smart Mirror — project rules

All agents must follow these rules on every task.

- This is a real workspace with shell and network. Run commands and use tools to investigate; do not only tell the user what to run.
- All commands must:
  - Be explained before execution (what and why)
  - Be logged with a short summary of results
  - Be retried with alternative approaches if they fail
- If something fails, diagnose, try alternatives, and retry rather than stopping after one attempt.

## Running log (persistent across iterations)

- Maintain a running log file for the task/session.
- The log must include:
  - Actions taken
  - Commands executed
  - Key outputs/results
  - Errors encountered and fixes attempted
  - Decisions made and reasoning
- Always read the existing log before continuing work.
- Append updates after every meaningful step.
- This log serves as shared memory across iterations and agents.


## Communication

- When referencing existing code, use Cursor code citations only in this form (with real line numbers and paths):

```12:15:src/example.ts
// cited lines
```

- Prefer markdown links for external URLs. Write in clear, complete sentences; keep length proportional to task complexity.
- Use bold and inline code sparingly for emphasis, not decoration.


##Reasoning about the task

- Use the full conversation: the latest message may refine work in progress rather than start something new.
- Infer goals and constraints from the thread, not only from the last message.
- Before making changes:
    - Identify existing patterns in the codebase
    - Confirm the simplest viable solution
    - Avoid introducing new abstractions unless necessary
    - Prefer simple, readable solutions over clever or complex ones.

## Code and changes

- Change only what the task requires. No drive-by refactors or unrelated files.
- Read surrounding code first; match naming, types, imports, and documentation level.
- When publishing code use PR on git.
- Reuse existing functions and patterns instead of duplicating logic.
- Every line in the diff should serve the request. Avoid verbose comments, docstrings on obvious code, and unnecessary defensive error handling unless clearly needed.
- Always test code in an isolated environment before finishing to ensure functionality is standard across programs.
- Never delete working functionality
- Write simply dont over complicate tasks. If the task is to ambitious please spawn subagents to break down the tasks and rewrite if unclear.

##Subagent usage
- Spawn subagents when:
    - The task spans multiple domains (UI, backend, hardware)
    - The task is large or ambiguous
    - Work can be parallelized
- Each subagent must have:
    - A clearly scoped goal
    - Defined inputs and expected outputs
- The parent agent must coordinate subagents, integrate results, and resolve conflicts.

##Testing and completion

- A task is only complete if:
    - Code runs without errors
    - Expected behavior is verified (not assumed)
    - No regressions are introduced
    - Results are clearly summarized
- Always run the code or simulate execution using available tools.
- If execution is not possible:
    - Explicitly state why
    - Describe what would be tested and how

##Hardware safety
- Do not interact with GPIO, camera, or hardware interfaces unless explicitly required.
- Simulate hardware interactions whenever possible.
- Any real hardware interaction must be clearly stated and justified before execution.

## Smart Mirror product context

- Raspberry Pi–based smart mirror: Up-and-Down UI, GPIO, camera, all stuff is handled locally for UI.
- Respect privacy (e.g. camera off unless the user explicitly activates it), consent for personal data, and responsiveness suitable for embedded hardware.

##UI constraints

- UI must be:
    - Modular
    - Vertical navigation only (up/down interaction model)
    - Readable at a distance (large text, high contrast)
    - Responsive on low-power hardware
- Avoid:
    - Complex nested layouts
    - Heavy animations
    - Browser-based UI unless explicitly required

##Performance constraints

- Minimize CPU and memory usage
- Avoid unnecessary background processes
- Prefer lightweight libraries
- Favor local computation over network calls